-- Zijin, China Southern, GF Securities, Sinopec, ICBC: China Stocks Preview
-- Bloomberg News
-- 2010-07-28T16:00:02Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-28/zijin-china-southern-airlines-co-sinopec-icbc-china-equity-preview.html

          
          
             The following companies may have
 unusual  price changes in China trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses, and share prices are as of the last close.  
 The  Shanghai Composite Index , which tracks the bigger of
China’s stock exchanges, gained 58.30, or 2.3 percent, to
2,633.66. The  CSI 300 Index  rose 2.4 percent to 2,863.72.  
 China Petroleum & Chemical Corp.  (600028 CH): A gasoline
service station in Nanjing run by the company wasn’t
“seriously” affected by an explosion at a plastics factory
owned by a local company, Jiangsu GPRO Group Co., the refiner
known as Sinopec said. China Petroleum, Asia’s biggest oil
refiner, rose 2.6 percent to 8.76 yuan.  
 China Southern Airlines Co.  (600029 CH): The company
expects an increase of over 5,000 percent in its profit for the
six months ended June 30, according to a statement to the Hong
Kong stock exchange. The shares climbed 4.1 percent to 7.37
yuan.  
 GF Securities Co.  (000776 CH): The company’s shares will
suspend trading today in Shenzhen pending an announcement about
a private share sale plan, the company said in a statement to
the city’s exchange. It expects shares to resume trading on Aug.
3, according to the statement.  
 The shares rose 3.1 percent to 32.98 yuan.  
 Industrial and Commercial Bank of China Ltd.  (601398 CH):
The Beijing-based lender said its board approved a rights offer
plan to raise up to 45 billion yuan ($6.6 billion) to replenish
capital. It will sell up to 0.6 shares for every 10 held, or as
many as 15.06 billion shares in Shanghai and 4.98 billion in
Hong Kong, according to a  statement  to the Shanghai stock
exchange.  
 The shares rose 1.9 percent to 4.36 yuan.  
 Zijin Mining Group Co.  (601899 CH): The company, which is
blamed for the industry’s worst waste leakage in China in two
years, said that the company’s Vice President  Chen Jiahong  was
detained on July 27 by the police in connection with a suspected
serious environmental crime. The stock gained 2.5 percent to
5.86 yuan.  
 -- Zhang Shidong ,  Judy Chen . Editor:  Glenn J. Kalinoski   
